{"parse":{"title":"Novel (Roman law)","pageid":25927289,"revid":858766047,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_law\" title=\"Roman law\">Roman law</a>, a <b>novel</b> (<a href=\"/wiki/Latin_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Latin language\">Latin</a>: <i><span lang=\"la\">novella constitutio</span></i>, \"new decree\"; <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\" title=\"Greek language\">Greek</a>: <span lang=\"el\">\u03bd\u03b5\u03b1\u03c1\u03ac</span>, <small><a href=\"/wiki/Romanization_of_Greek\" title=\"Romanization of Greek\">translit.</a>&#160;</small><i lang=\"el-Latn\" title=\"Greek-language transliteration\">neara</i>) is a new decree or edict,<sup id=\"cite_ref-ODB_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ODB-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> in other words a new law. The term was used from the fourth century AD onwards and was specifically used for laws issued after the publishing of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Codex_Theodosianus\" title=\"Codex Theodosianus\">Codex Theodosianus</a></i> in 438 and then for the Justiniac Novels, or <i><a href=\"/wiki/Novellae_Constitutiones\" title=\"Novellae Constitutiones\">Novellae Constitutiones</a></i>. The term was used on and off in later Roman history until falling out of use during the <a href=\"/wiki/Late-Byzantine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Late-Byzantine\">late Byzantine period</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ODB_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ODB-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Novel_(Roman_law)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Constitution_(Roman_law)\" title=\"Constitution (Roman law)\">Constitution (Roman law)</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Novel_(Roman_law)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-ODB-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-ODB_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ODB_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFKazhdan1991\" class=\"citation encyclopaedia\"><a href=\"/wiki/Alexander_Kazhdan\" title=\"Alexander Kazhdan\">Kazhdan, Alexander</a> (1991). \"Novel\".  In <a href=\"/wiki/Alexander_Kazhdan\" title=\"Alexander Kazhdan\">Kazhdan, Alexander</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Oxford_Dictionary_of_Byzantium\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium\">The Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium</a></i>. Oxford and New York: Oxford University Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-19-504652-8\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-19-504652-8\">0-19-504652-8</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Novel&amp;rft.btitle=The+Oxford+Dictionary+of+Byzantium&amp;rft.place=Oxford+and+New+York&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1991&amp;rft.isbn=0-19-504652-8&amp;rft.aulast=Kazhdan&amp;rft.aufirst=Alexander&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANovel+%28Roman+law%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=